text: A fundamental tenet of linguistic science is that the sound of a word has a purely arbitrary connection to the word 's meaning [ 1 ] , [ 2 ] .
label: det amod nsubj case amod nmod cop mark det nsubj case det nmod root det advmod amod obj case det nmod case nmod punct dep punct punct punct dep punct punct

text: Thus , the sound of the word dog in English is connected to the concept ‚Äò dog ‚Äô by historical accident and not by any natural connection ; roughly the same concept is just as well denoted in French by chien , in German by hund , and in Japanese by inu .
label: advmod punct det nsubj case det nmod appos case nmod aux root case det obl punct appos punct case amod obl cc advmod case det amod conj punct advmod det amod nsubj aux advmod advmod advmod parataxis case obl case obl punct case conj case orphan punct cc case conj case orphan punct

text: But it is not that a word can have just any vocal sound .
label: cc nsubj cop advmod mark det nsubj aux root advmod det amod obj punct

text: While the possibility space for sound systems of the world 's language is enormous , any given language makes use of only a restricted portion of the possible sounds [ 3 ] , [ 4 ] .
label: mark det compound nsubj case compound nmod case det nmod case nmod cop advcl punct det amod nsubj root obj case advmod det amod nmod case det amod nmod punct dep punct punct punct dep punct punct

text: It follows from these two basic principles ‚Äì the ‚Äò arbitrariness of the sign ‚Äô , and the ‚Äò selectiveness of particular sound systems ‚Äô ‚Äì that the words that exist in the world 's languages should sound quite different from each other , and that the likelihood that there are universal words is extremely small .

text: But in this study we present a striking exception to this otherwise robust rule .

text: Mutation - based testing [ 1 ] is a test technique that involves artificially introducing errors into a System Under Test ( SUT ) .

text: In this article , we propose mutation operators specific to the domain of Geographic Information Systems ( GIS ) applications .

text: Replication in Second Language Research :
label: root case amod compound nmod punct

text: Narrative and Systematic Reviews and Recommendations for the Field
label: amod cc conj root cc conj case det nmod

text: Replication studies are considered by many to play a fundamental role in any scientific endeavor .
label: compound nsubj aux root case obl mark xcomp det amod obj case det amod obl punct

text: When using the same materials and procedures as a previous study , replication studies serve to test the reliability of the previous study ‚Äôs findings .
label: advmod advcl det amod obj cc conj case det amod nmod punct compound nsubj root mark xcomp det obj case det amod nmod case nmod punct

text: When altering specific methodological or participant characteristics of a previous study , they serve to test generalizability of the earlier findings under different conditions .
label: advmod advcl amod amod cc conj obj case det amod obl punct nsubj root mark xcomp obj case det amod nmod case amod nmod punct

text: One indication of the importance of replication is found in the 50 or more calls for replication research in the field of second language ( L2 ) research alone ( see references for 50 calls and commentaries in Appendix S1 in the Supporting Information online ) : from Santos ( 1989 ) through Polio and Gass 1997 to very recent proposals for specific replication studies , such as Vandergrift and Cross 2017 and even a book - length treatment ( Porte , 2012 ) .
label: nummod nsubj case det nmod case nmod aux root case det nummod cc conj obl case compound nmod case det nmod case amod compound punct appos punct nmod advmod punct dep obj case nummod nmod cc conj case compound obl case det amod nmod advmod punct punct case nmod punct nmod punct case nmod cc conj nmod case advmod amod nmod case amod compound nmod punct case fixed nmod cc conj nmod cc advmod det compound punct compound conj punct dep punct nmod punct punct

text: Beyond these calls , efforts to actively promote and facilitate replication studies have also emerged .
label: case det obl punct nsubj mark advmod acl cc conj compound obj aux advmod root punct

text: For example , the Instruments for Research into Second Languages ( IRIS ) repository ( http://www.irisdatabase.org ) was established in 2011 and holds , at the time of writing , over 3,800 materials that can be used for replication , among other purposes , in L2 research ( Marsden & Mackey , 2014 ; Marsden , Mackey , & Plonsky , 2016 ) .
label: case obl punct det compound case nmod case amod nmod punct appos punct nsubj punct appos punct aux root case obl cc conj punct case det obl mark acl punct advmod nummod obj nsubj aux aux acl case obl punct case amod obl punct case compound obl punct dep cc conj punct nmod punct conj punct conj punct cc conj punct nmod punct punct

text: The Open Science Framework ( https://osf.io ) , also established in 2011 , provides a web infrastructure to facilitate collaboration and has been used for large replication efforts in psychology ( e.g. , Open Science Collaboration , 2015 ) , which continue to make waves in academia ( Laws , 2016 ; Lindsay , 2015 ; Martin & Clarke , 2017 ) and the general media ( Baker , 2015 ; Devlin , 2016 ) .
label: det amod compound nsubj punct appos punct punct advmod acl case obl punct root det compound obj mark advcl obj cc aux aux conj case amod compound obl case nmod punct advmod punct amod compound dep punct nmod punct punct nsubj acl mark xcomp obj case obl punct dep punct nmod punct conj punct nmod punct conj cc conj punct nmod punct cc det amod conj punct dep punct nmod punct conj punct nmod punct punct

text: In some fields , a flourishing metascience , that is , the scientific study of science ( see Munaf√≤ et al. , 2017 ) , has included syntheses assessing the quantity and nature of replication efforts , for example , in education ( Makel & Plucker , 2014 and in psychology ( Makel et al. , 2012 ) .
label: case det obl punct det amod nsubj punct advmod fixed punct det amod appos case nmod punct parataxis obj cc conj punct nmod punct punct aux root obj acl det obj cc conj case compound nmod punct case nmod punct case obl punct dep cc conj punct nmod cc case conj punct dep cc conj punct nmod punct punct

text: The driving force behind this battery of calls , commentaries , infrastructure , and metascience is a perceived crisis in the state of replication research .
label: det amod nsubj case det nmod case nmod punct conj punct conj punct cc conj cop det amod root case det nmod case compound nmod punct

text: The severe concerns underpinning the alleged crisis have several dimensions relating to : (a) the ( small ) amount of published replication research ; (b) the ( poor ) quality of replication research ; and (c) the ( lack of ) reproducibility , which refers to the extent to which findings can ( not ) be reproduced in replication attempts that have been undertaken .
label: det amod nsubj acl det amod obj root amod obj acl case punct dep det punct amod punct obl case amod compound nmod punct dep det punct amod punct conj case compound nmod punct cc dep det punct conj case punct nmod punct nsubj acl case det obl case obl nsubj aux punct advmod punct aux acl case compound obl nsubj aux aux acl punct

text: These concerns speak to the very core of science , raising fundamental questions about the validity and reliability of our work .
label: det nsubj root case det amod obl case nmod punct advcl amod obj case det nmod cc conj case nmod nmod punct

text: Indeed , some commentators have called replication the ‚Äú gold standard ‚Äù of research evidence ( Jasny , Chin , Chong , & Vignieri , 2011 , p. 1225 ) and a ‚Äú linchpin of the scientific process ‚Äù ( Let ‚Äôs replicate , 2006 , p. 330 ) .
label: advmod punct det nsubj aux root obj det punct compound xcomp punct case compound nmod punct dep punct conj punct conj punct cc conj punct nmod punct dep dep punct cc det punct conj case det amod nmod punct punct dep obj xcomp punct obl punct dep dep punct punct

text: In the field of L2 research , given the importance of replication and the 50 calls for replication in L2 research that we identified , one might expect a substantial number of published replication studies by now .
label: case det obl case compound nmod punct advcl det obj case nmod cc det nummod conj case nmod case compound nmod obj nsubj acl punct nsubj aux root det amod obj case amod compound nmod case obl punct

text: However , a perceived lack of prestige , excitement , and originality of replication plagues L2 research ( Porte , 2012 ) , as it does other disciplines ( Berez - Kroeker et al. , 2017 ; Branco , Cohen , Vossen , Ide , & Calzolari , 2017 ; Chambers , 2017 ; Schmidt , 2009 ) , and these perceptions are thought to have caused , at least in part ( directly or indirectly ) , alleged low rates and a poor quality of published replication studies .
label: advmod punct det amod nsubj case nmod punct conj punct cc conj case nmod root compound obj punct dep punct nmod punct punct mark nsubj advcl amod obj punct dep punct flat cc conj punct nmod punct conj punct conj punct conj punct conj punct cc conj punct nmod punct conj punct nmod punct conj punct nmod punct punct cc det nsubj aux conj mark aux xcomp punct case nmod case obl punct advmod cc conj punct punct amod amod obj cc det amod conj case amod compound nmod punct

text: However , a systematic metascience on replication research has not yet been established in the field of L2 research , leaving a poor understanding of the actual number and nature of replication studies that have been published .
label: advmod punct det amod nsubj case compound nmod aux advmod advmod aux root case det obl case compound nmod punct advcl det amod obj case det amod nmod cc conj case compound nmod nsubj aux aux acl punct

text: The current study begins to address this gap through narrative and systematic reviews .
label: det amod nsubj root mark xcomp det obj case amod cc conj obl punct

text: The narrative review considers challenges in replication research and is largely informed by commentaries and metascience from psychology , given that the cognitive and social subdomains of psychology are highly influential in L2 research , and also from education , another key sister discipline .
label: det amod nsubj root obj case compound nmod cc aux advmod conj case obl cc conj case nmod punct advcl mark det amod cc conj nsubj case nmod cop advmod ccomp case compound obl punct cc advmod case conj punct det amod compound appos punct

text: The narrative review is organized around four broad themes : (a) the quantity of replication research , (b) the nature of replication research , (c) the relationship between initial and replication studies , and (d) the interpretation and extent of reproducibility of the findings of initial studies .
label: det amod nsubj aux root case nummod amod obl punct dep det appos case compound nmod punct dep det conj case compound nmod punct dep det conj case amod cc conj nmod punct cc dep det conj cc conj case nmod case det nmod case amod nmod punct

text: To gain insight into these issues in the context of L2 research , the systematic review provides a synthesis of L2 studies in journal articles that self - labeled as replications .
label: mark advcl obj case det nmod case det obl case compound nmod punct det amod nsubj root det obj case compound nmod case compound nmod nsubj compound punct acl case obl punct

text: The research questions and methods of the systematic review were largely determined by the narrative review but also emerged through the design and piloting of the coding instrument .
label: det compound nsubj cc conj case det amod nmod aux advmod root case det amod obl cc advmod conj case det obl cc conj case det amod nmod punct

text: Finally , we offer further discussion and 16 recommendations for future replication work that draw on our narrative and systematic reviews and on our experience of carrying out multisite ( Morgan - Short et al. , 2018 ) 1 and single site ( Faretta - Stutenberg & Morgan - Short , 2011 ; Marsden , Williams , & Liu , 2013 ; McManus & Marsden , 2017 ; Morgan - Short , Heil , Botero - Moriaty , & Ebert , 2012 ) replications .
label: advmod punct nsubj root amod obj cc nummod conj case amod compound nmod nsubj acl case nmod amod cc conj obl cc case nmod conj mark acl compound amod punct dep punct flat cc conj punct nmod punct dep cc amod conj punct dep punct flat cc conj punct flat punct nmod punct conj punct conj punct cc conj punct nmod punct conj cc conj punct nmod punct conj punct flat punct conj punct conj punct flat punct cc conj punct nmod punct obj punct

text: We start from the widely agreed premise that testing the reproducibility of findings should have an essential role in the testing and refinement of theory , at least for hypothesis - testing epistemologies that seek to ascertain generalizability and for other epistemologies in which constructs are deemed to be definable and observable .
label: nsubj root case det advmod amod obl mark csubj det obj case nmod aux acl det amod obj case det nmod cc conj case nmod punct advmod fixed case compound punct compound nmod nsubj acl mark xcomp obj cc case amod conj case obl nsubj aux acl mark cop xcomp cc conj punct

text: Thus , our overall aim is to provide conceptual clarification and an empirical base for future discussion and production of replication studies , with a view to improving the amount and quality of L2 replication research .
label: advmod punct nmod amod nsubj cop mark root amod obj cc det amod conj case amod obl cc conj case compound nmod punct case det obl mark acl det obj cc conj case compound compound nmod punct

text: 1. Introduction
label: dep root

text: Salinity is one of the most important marine parameters , which controls many processes such as physical circulations , biogeochemistry dynamics from regional to global ocean [ 1 , 2 ] .
label: nsubj cop root case det advmod amod amod nmod punct nsubj acl amod obj case fixed amod nmod punct compound conj case amod case obl obl punct dep punct conj punct punct

text: Although drifters and buoys , together with cruises , have accumulated large amount in - situ water salinity data in different regions , it is still difficult to monitor global ocean salinity with high temporal - spatial resolution by the in situ measurements .
label: mark nsubj cc conj punct advmod case obl punct aux advcl amod obj amod punct flat compound compound nmod case amod obl punct expl cop advmod root mark csubj amod compound obj case amod compound punct amod obl case det amod flat obl punct

text: In the past decade , with the successful launch of the soil moisture and ocean salinity ( SMOS ) satellite by the European Space Agency ( ESA ) [ 3 ] , the Aquarius / SAC-D satellite [ 4 ] , and the soil moisture active passive ( SMAP ) satellite [ 5 , 6 ] by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration ( NASA ) , global sea surface salinity ( SSS ) observations from space have become possible and a significant improvement has been made to understand the ocean dynamics and climate change .
label: case det amod obl punct case det amod obl case det compound compound cc compound conj punct appos punct nmod case det amod compound nmod punct appos punct punct dep punct punct det compound cc conj conj punct dep punct punct cc det compound compound amod amod punct parataxis punct conj punct dep punct conj punct case det amod compound cc conj nmod punct appos punct punct amod compound compound compound punct appos punct nsubj case nmod aux root xcomp cc det amod nsubj aux aux conj mark advcl det compound obj cc compound conj punct

text: The early concept of remote sensing of SSS has been demonstrated in the late 1970s with observations by Skylab [ 7 ] and two airborne L - band radiometry experiments [ 8 , 9 ] .
label: det amod nsubj case amod nmod case nmod aux aux root case det amod obl case obl case nmod punct dep punct cc nummod amod compound punct compound compound conj punct dep punct conj punct punct

text: At the end of 1990 , two airborne microwave interferometers , the electronically scanned thinned array radiometer ( ESTAR ) and the scanning low - frequency microwave radiometer ( SLFMR ) , successfully produced SSS maps in coastal areas in agreement with in - situ measurements with an accuracy of about 1 psu .
label: case det obl case nmod punct nummod amod compound nsubj punct det advmod amod amod compound appos punct appos punct cc det amod amod punct compound compound conj punct appos punct punct advmod root compound obj case amod nmod case obl case amod punct flat nmod case det obl case advmod nummod nmod punct

text: Based on many experiments , the L - band is evidenced as the optimal frequency for remote sensing of SSS , which has been adopted by SMOS , Aquarius / SAC-D and SMAP .
label: advcl case amod obl punct det compound punct nsubj aux root case det amod obl case amod nmod case nmod punct nsubj aux aux acl case obl punct conj cc conj cc conj punct

text: However , the sensitivity of satellite measured brightness temperature to SSS is quite low .
label: advmod punct det nsubj case compound amod compound nmod case nmod cop advmod root punct

text: For example , the sensitivity of vertically polarized brightness temperature to SSS variation is 0.4 to 0.8 K/psu for different observing angles and sea surface temperatures ( SST ) , and it is only 0.2 to 0.6 K/psu for the horizontal polarization brightness temperature [ 10 ] .
label: case nmod punct det nsubj case advmod amod compound nmod case compound nmod cop nummod case nmod root case amod compound obl cc compound compound conj punct appos punct punct cc nsubj cop advmod nummod case nmod conj case det amod compound compound obl punct dep punct punct

text: Thus , remote sensing of SSS requires a highly accurate retrieval model .
label: advmod punct amod nsubj case nmod root det advmod amod compound obj punct

text: It is widely accepted that the corrections of the sea surface and atmospheric effects are essential for remote sensing of SSS , since these effects could alter the value of sensor - measured brightness temperature and introduce errors into the SSS retrieval process .
label: expl aux advmod root mark det nsubj case det compound compound cc conj nmod cop csubj case amod obl case nmod punct mark det nsubj aux advcl det obj case compound punct amod compound nmod cc conj obj case det compound compound obl punct

text: Besides the atmospheric effects , the increasing of sea surface emissivity due to the sea surface roughness and foam effects is the main source of error , which could significantly hamper the accuracy of SSS retrieval [ 11 ] .
label: case det amod obl punct det nsubj case compound compound nmod case fixed det compound compound nmod cc compound conj cop det amod root case nmod punct nsubj aux advmod acl det obj case compound nmod punct dep punct punct

text: Over the past decades , the correction for sea surface roughness effects were studied based on the in - situ and airborne measurements ; for example , the experiments made from a tower [ 12 ] , wind and salinity experiments ( WISE ) [ 13 , 14 ] , airborne Passive - Active L - band Sensor ( PALS ) campaign [ 15 ] and Combined Airborne Radio instruments for Ocean and Land Studies ( CAROLS ) campaigns [ 16 , 17 ] .
label: case det amod obl punct det nsubj case compound compound compound nmod aux root advcl case det amod punct flat cc conj obl punct case obl punct det parataxis acl case det obl punct dep punct punct compound cc conj conj punct parataxis punct punct dep punct conj punct punct amod amod punct amod compound punct compound compound punct appos punct conj punct dep punct cc amod amod compound compound case compound cc conj nmod punct appos punct conj punct dep punct conj punct punct

text: Many rough surface emission models have also been developed based on the theoretical and empirical methods .
label: amod amod compound compound nsubj aux advmod aux root advcl case det amod cc conj obl punct

text: Among these models , the small - slope approximation / small perturbation model ( SSA / SPM ) [ 18 , 19 , 20 , 21 ] , two scale model ( TSM ) [ 22 , 23 , 24 ] and empirical / semi-empirical models [ 25 , 26 ] have been widely used by the research community and implemented in different satellite data processing systems .
label: case det obl punct det amod punct compound compound cc amod conj nsubj punct appos cc conj punct punct dep punct conj punct conj punct conj punct punct nummod compound conj punct appos punct punct dep punct conj punct conj punct cc amod cc conj conj punct dep punct conj punct aux aux advmod root case det compound obl cc conj case amod compound compound compound obl punct

text: As the foam effect is significant at high wind speed conditions ( above a threshold of 12 m / s ) due to strong wave breaking , it has been corrected by numerous models ; for example , the semi-empirical models [ 27 , 28 ] and radiative transfer equation ( RTE ) based models [ 29 , 30 ] , which were developed to estimate the foam covered sea surface emissivity .
label: mark det compound nsubj cop advcl case amod compound compound obl punct case det parataxis case nummod nmod case nmod punct case fixed amod compound obl punct nsubj aux aux root case amod obl punct case obl punct det amod parataxis punct dep punct conj punct cc amod compound compound punct appos punct amod conj punct dep punct conj punct punct nsubj aux acl mark advcl det compound amod compound compound obj punct

text: Although many theoretical and empirical models have been developed , some problems are still unsolved .
label: mark amod amod cc conj nsubj aux aux advcl punct det nsubj cop advmod root punct

text: For example , the TSM originally proposed to estimate brightness temperature at higher frequencies , uses the sea surface wave spectrum by multiplying a factor of 2 .
label: case obl punct det nsubj advmod acl mark advcl compound obj case amod obl punct root det compound compound compound obj mark advcl det obj case nmod punct

text: However , whether this modification can be applied to L - band is still unclear , and the choice of cutoff wavenumber is arbitrary and needs to be clarified in the L - band .
label: advmod punct mark det nsubj aux aux csubj case compound punct obl cop advmod root punct cc det nsubj case compound nmod cop conj cc conj mark aux xcomp case det compound punct obl punct

text: Moreover , the sea surface reflection of downwelling atmospheric emission is another contribution to satellite - observed brightness temperature [ 31 ] , thus the determination of the cutoff wavenumber is required not only for sea surface emission but also for reflection .
label: advmod punct det compound compound nsubj case amod amod nmod cop det root case compound punct amod compound nmod punct dep punct punct advmod det nsubj case det compound nmod aux parataxis advmod advmod case compound compound obl cc advmod case conj punct

text: In addition , the widely used empirical models decouple the wind effect from SSS and SST effects , which means that the surface emission is due to a perfectly flat sea surface and the wind - roughened sea surface .
label: case obl punct det advmod amod amod nsubj root det compound obj case compound cc conj obl punct nsubj advcl mark det compound nsubj cop case fixed det advmod amod compound ccomp cc det compound punct amod compound conj punct

text: The wind - roughened sea surface is associated with the increased brightness temperature ( due to sea surface roughness effect ) , which induces regional biases when applied to different areas [ 32 ] .
label: det compound punct amod compound nsubj aux root case det amod compound obl punct case fixed compound compound compound nmod punct punct nsubj acl amod obj advmod advcl case amod obl punct dep punct punct

text: Furthermore , the satellite measurements of SSS are hampered by the effect of radio frequency interference ( RFI ) in offshore areas of China ( i.e. , Bohai sea , Yellow sea and East China sea ) , which causes a large amount of data to be discarded [ 33 ] .
label: advmod punct det compound nsubj case nmod aux root case det obl case compound compound nmod punct appos punct case amod nmod case nmod punct advmod punct compound appos punct amod conj cc compound compound conj punct punct nsubj acl det amod iobj case nmod mark aux xcomp punct dep punct punct

text: Thus , the compatibility of these models in coastal area of China needs to be assessed and tested in order to achieve higher accuracies of SSS from the space - borne observations .
label: advmod punct det nsubj case det nmod case amod nmod case nmod root mark aux xcomp cc conj mark fixed mark advcl amod obj case nmod case det compound punct amod obl punct

text: Discussion
label: root

text: We have shown that the addition of an artificial tail during ontogeny can produce postural and locomotory changes in chickens , consistent with the posture and kinematics inferred for non-avian dinosaurs [ 5 ] , [ 6 ] , [ 11 ] .
label: nsubj aux root mark det nsubj case det amod nmod case nmod aux ccomp amod cc conj obj case nmod punct amod case det obl cc conj acl case amod obl punct dep punct punct punct dep punct punct punct dep punct punct

text: The posterior displacement of the CoM produced a more vertically oriented femur during standing ( femur in experimental animals was 40 % more vertical than control subjects ) , and increased femoral retraction and decreased knee flexion during walking .
label: det amod nsubj case det nmod root det advmod advmod amod obj case obl punct nsubj case amod nmod cop nummod obl advmod parataxis case compound obl punct punct cc conj amod obj cc conj compound obj case obl punct

text: These results indicate a shift from the standard bird , knee - driven bipedal locomotion to a more hip - driven locomotion , typical of crocodilians ( the only other extant archosaur group ) , mammals , and hypothetically , bipedal non-avian dinosaurs .
label: det nsubj root det obj case det amod compound punct compound punct amod amod nmod case det advmod obl punct amod nmod punct amod case obl punct det advmod amod amod compound appos punct punct conj punct cc advmod punct amod amod conj punct

text: These postural and kinematics changes can not be attributed to an increased weight as subjects of the control - weight group did not show the same changes as the experimental group .
label: det amod cc conj nsubj aux advmod aux root case det amod obl mark nsubj case det compound punct compound nmod aux advmod advcl det amod obj case det amod nmod punct

text: In fact , the control - weight subjects showed a more horizontally oriented femur during walking with respect to the control group , similar to that observed in Carrano and Biewener 's experimental subjects [ 7 ] .
label: case obl punct det compound punct compound nsubj root det advmod advmod amod obj case obl case obl case det compound nmod punct amod case obl acl case nmod cc conj case amod obl punct dep punct punct

text: Therefore , we conclude that the location of the CoM can be a key factor in defining limb posture and kinematics .
label: advmod punct nsubj root mark det nsubj case det nmod aux cop det amod ccomp mark acl compound obj cc conj punct

text: It has been proposed that the relative mass of the CFL can be used as a proxy to estimate the relative importance of femoral retraction during locomotion in extinct bipedal dinosaurs [ 8 ] .
label: expl aux aux root mark det amod nsubj case det nmod aux aux csubj case det obl mark advcl det amod obj case amod nmod case nmod case amod amod nmod punct dep punct punct

text: Our data show that for a given CFL mass , femoral retraction can be greatly affected by the location of the CoM and limb postures .
label: nmod nsubj root mark case det amod compound obl punct amod nsubj aux aux advmod ccomp case det obl case det nmod cc compound conj punct

text: Furthermore , limb retraction can be markedly modulated with speed [ 5 ] , suggesting caution when using simple morphological parameters to estimate functional relationships .
label: advmod punct compound nsubj aux aux advmod root case obl punct dep punct punct advcl obj advmod acl amod amod obj mark advcl amod obj punct

text: Theories
label: root

text: Nida has been a pioneer in the fields of translation theory and linguistics .
label: nsubj aux cop det root case det nmod case compound nmod cc conj punct

text: His Ph.D. dissertation , A Synopsis of English Syntax , was the first full - scale analysis of a major language according to the " immediate - constituent " theory .
label: nmod compound nsubj punct det appos case amod nmod punct cop det amod amod punct compound root case det amod nmod case fixed det punct amod punct compound punct nmod punct

text: His textbook Morphology : The Descriptive Analysis of Words was one of the major works of American Structuralism .
label: nmod nsubj appos punct det compound dep case nmod cop root case det amod nmod case amod nmod punct

text: It remained the only thorough introduction to the field for decades and is still valuable for its many examples and exercises .
label: nsubj root det amod amod xcomp case det nmod case obl cc cop advmod conj case nmod amod obl cc conj punct

text: His most notable contribution to translation theory is Dynamic Equivalence , also known as Functional Equivalence .
label: nmod advmod amod nsubj case compound nmod cop amod root punct advmod acl case amod obl punct

text: For more information , see " Dynamic and formal equivalence . "
label: case amod obl punct root punct amod cc conj obj punct punct

text: Nida also developed the componential analysis technique , which split words into their components to help determine equivalence in translation ( e.g. " bachelor " = male + unmarried ) .

text: This is , perhaps , not the best example of the technique , though it is the most well - known .
label: nsubj cop punct advmod punct advmod det amod root case det nmod punct mark nsubj cop det advmod advmod punct advcl punct

text: Nida 's dynamic - equivalence theory is often held in opposition to the views of philologists who maintain that an understanding of the source text ( ST ) can be achieved by assessing the inter-animation of words on the page , and that meaning is self - contained within the text ( i.e. much more focused on achieving semantic equivalence ) .
label: nmod case amod punct compound nsubj aux advmod root case obl case det nmod case nmod nsubj acl mark det nsubj case det compound nmod punct appos punct aux aux ccomp mark advcl det obj case nmod case det nmod punct cc mark nsubj cop compound punct conj case det obl punct advmod advmod advmod parataxis mark advcl amod obj punct punct

text: This theory , along with other theories of correspondence in translating , are elaborated in his essay Principles of Correspondence , where Nida begins by asserting that given that " no two languages are identical , either in the meanings given to corresponding symbols or in the ways in which symbols are arranged in phrases and sentences , it stands to reason that there can be no absolute correspondence between languages .
label: det nsubj punct advmod case amod obl case nmod mark acl punct aux root case nmod obl appos case nmod punct advmod nsubj acl mark advcl mark advcl mark punct det nummod nsubj cop ccomp punct cc case det obl acl case amod obl cc case det conj case obl nsubj aux acl case obl cc conj punct expl ccomp case obl mark expl aux cop det amod csubj case nmod punct

text: Hence , there can be no fully exact translations . "
label: advmod punct expl aux root det advmod amod nsubj punct punct

text: While the impact of a translation may be close to the original , there can be no identity in detail .
label: mark det nsubj case det nmod aux cop advcl case det obl punct expl aux root det nsubj case nmod punct

text: Nida then sets forth the differences in translation , as he would account for it , within three basic factors :
label: nsubj advmod root compound det obj case nmod punct mark nsubj aux advcl case obl punct case nummod amod obl punct

text: 1. The nature of the message : in some messages the content is of primary consideration , and in others the form must be given a higher priority .
label: dep det root case det nmod punct case det obl det nsubj cop case amod parataxis punct cc case obl det nsubj aux aux conj det amod obj punct

text: 2. The purpose of the author and of the translator : to give information on both form and content ; to aim at full intelligibility of the reader so he / she may understand the full implications of the message ; for imperative purposes that aim at not just understanding the translation but also at ensuring no misunderstanding of the translation .
label: dep det root case det nmod cc case det conj punct mark parataxis obj case cc obl cc conj punct mark conj case amod obl case det nmod mark nsubj cc conj aux advcl det amod obj case det nmod punct case amod conj nsubj acl mark advmod advmod advcl det obj cc advmod mark conj det obj case det nmod punct

text: 3. The type of audience : prospective audiences differ both in decoding ability and in potential interest .
label: dep det root case nmod punct amod nsubj parataxis cc case compound obl cc case amod conj punct

text: Nida brings in the reminder that while there are no such things as " identical equivalents " in translating , what one must in translating seek to do is find the " closest natural equivalent " .
label: nsubj root compound det obj mark mark expl advcl det amod nsubj case punct amod nmod punct mark acl punct nsubj nsubj aux mark advcl acl mark xcomp cop acl det punct amod amod obj punct punct

text: Here he identifies two basic orientations in translating based on two different types of equivalence :
label: advmod nsubj root nummod amod obj mark acl advcl case nummod amod obl case nmod punct

text: Formal Equivalence ( F - E ) and Dynamic Equivalence ( D - E ) .
label: amod root punct appos punct flat punct cc amod conj punct appos punct flat punct punct

text: F - E focuses attention on the message itself , in both form and content .
label: nsubj punct flat root obj case det obl nmod punct case cc obl cc conj punct

text: Such translations then would be concerned with such correspondences as poetry to poetry , sentence to sentence , and concept to concept .
label: amod nsubj advmod aux aux root case amod obl case nmod case nmod punct conj case nmod punct cc conj case nmod punct

text: Such a formal orientation that typifies this type of structural equivalence is called a " gloss translation " in which the translator aims at reproducing as literally and meaningfully as possible the form and content of the original .
label: det det amod nsubj nsubj acl det obj case amod nmod aux root det punct compound xcomp punct case obl det nsubj acl mark advcl advmod advmod cc conj mark advcl det obj cc conj case det nmod punct

text: The principles governing an F - E translation would then be : reproduction of grammatical units ; consistency in word usage ; and meanings in terms of the source context .

text: Theodorus of Tabennese ( c. 314 ‚Äì 368 ) , also known as Abba Theodorus and Theodore the Sanctified was the spiritual successor to Pachomius and played a crucial role in preventing the first Christian cenobitic monastic federation from collapsing after the death of its founder .

text: Biography

text: According to hagiography , Theodorus was born into a wealthy Christian family and was well educated from a young age .

text: This is a fun one .

text: On the NATO conference , well I mean the obvious question is why should NATO exist ?

text: In fact you can ask questions about why it should ever have existed , but now why should it exist .

text: I mean the theory was , whether you believe it or not , that it would be a defensive alliance against potential Soviet aggression , that ‚Äôs the basic doctrine .

text: When the Soviet Union collapsed there had been an agreement , a recent agreement , between Gorbachev and the U.S government and the first Bush administration .

text: The agreement was that Gorbachev agreed to a quite remarkable concession : he agreed to let a united Germany join the NATO military alliance .

text: Now it is remarkable in the light of history , the history of the past century , Germany alone had virtually destroyed Russia , twice , and Germany backed by a hostile military alliance , centered in the most phenomenal military power in history , that ‚Äôs a real threat .

text: Well that ‚Äôs a significant threat to the Soviet Union , to Russia now that there was no longer any Soviet Union , it was a significant threat to Russia and not surprisingly they responded by beefing up their offensive capacity , not much but some .
label: discourse nsubj cop det amod root case det compound nmod punct case nmod advmod mark expl advcl advmod advmod det compound nsubj punct nsubj cop det amod parataxis case nmod cc advmod advmod nsubj conj mark advcl compound nmod amod obj punct advmod advmod cc conj punct

text: For our readers who are unaware of your site , could you briefly explain what wikiHow is ?

text: wikiHow is a collaborative effort to build the world 's largest , highest quality how - to manual .

text: Our long term goal is to produce practical instructions on almost every topic in every language .

text: Like Wikipedia , wikiHow is a wiki that runs on Mediawiki software .

text: Our community is full of volunteers from all over the world .

text: That said , we are quite different from Wikipedia in several respects :
label: nsubj advcl punct nsubj cop advmod root case obl case amod obl punct

text: Why did you decide to create wikiHow ?
label: advmod aux nsubj root mark xcomp obj punct

text: I think that providing people with a practical education is one of the most empowering things you can offer a person .

text: How much more could you accomplish as an individual if you could learn any activity ?

text: I think that building a universal how - to manual would be a tremendous gift for the world .

text: I 've been interested in building a comprehensive how - to manual long before I first envisioned wikiHow .

text: My first attempt at building this resource was a website I used to run called eHow .
label: nmod amod nsubj mark acl det obj cop det root nsubj acl mark xcomp acl xcomp punct

text: eHow was and continues to be the largest and how to website in the world .

text: eHow contains copyrighted content run on proprietary software .

text: When I ran eHow , the content was professionally produced and edited .

text: This business model worked for producing content on topics that appeal to advertisers in languages like English that have large advertising markets .

text: However , paying people to write and edit articles ultimately means that you have to make one of two sacrifices .
label: advmod punct csubj iobj mark xcomp cc conj obj advmod root mark nsubj ccomp mark xcomp obj case nummod nmod punct

text: You either 1) sacrifice on breadth and do n't produce the topics that wo n't interest advertisers , or 2) you sacrifice on quality and produce content that does n't cost much to write .

label: nsubj cop advmod root mark advcl obj case det nmod punct mark nsubj advcl det nmod case compound acl nsubj ccomp mark cop amod xcomp cc conj punct

text: So ultimately I decided that eHow 's model would not build the resource I envisioned .

text: Why did you decide to use a Creative Commons license ?
label: advmod aux nsubj root mark xcomp det amod compound obj punct

text: We use a Creative Commons license to give our community the right to fork ( http://www.wikihow.com/wikiHow:Right-to-Fork ) .

label: mark compound nsubj advcl nmod nsubj aux ccomp case det amod obl punct nsubj aux root det det obj cc det det conj cc conj det obj xcomp punct

text: This is possible because we release all of our software under the Open Source GPL license and release our content under a Creative Commons license .
label: nsubj cop root mark nsubj advcl obj case nmod nmod case det amod compound compound obl cc conj nmod obj case det amod compound obl punct

text: I believe that offering this right to fork has been a key element of our success thus far .
label: nsubj root mark csubj det obj mark acl aux cop det amod ccomp case nmod nmod advmod advmod punct

text: That said , when we started out I did n't know the difference between the GNU Free Document License and my California Driver 's license .

text: As a result , we made some mistakes along the path .

text: wikiHow achieved this popularity for a few reasons .

text: First , people around the world are desperate for high quality how - to information .

text: Sports in the United States largely reaffirm existing relations of power in society .

text: The impact depends on a number of aspects .

text: Scientists analyse effects of global warming , atmospheric ozone on crops

text: Monday , July 28 , 2014
label: root punct compound appos punct nmod

text: A research team from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Colorado State University of the US and the University of Sheffield of the UK has analysed effects of global warming and ozone pollution over 2000 - 2050 on the worldwide production of wheat , rice , maize and soybean .
label: det compound nsubj case det compound nmod case nmod cc compound compound conj case det nmod cc det conj case nmod case det nmod aux root obj case amod nmod cc compound conj case nmod case nmod case det amod nmod case nmod punct conj punct conj cc conj punct

text: The study was published in journal Nature Climate Change yesterday .
label: det nsubj aux root case obl compound compound appos obl punct

text: The scientists found reduction of crop yields by 2050 exceeded 10 % of 2000 levels , substantially decreasing food security , in all cases examined .
label: det nsubj root nsubj case compound nmod case nmod ccomp nummod obj case compound nmod punct advmod advcl compound obj punct case det obl acl punct

text: Several scenarios were considered because of uncertainty of future levels of ozone pollution .
label: amod nsubj aux root case fixed obl case amod nmod case compound nmod punct

text: They estimated by 2050 , increasing population and changing diet would increase world food needs by 50 percent .
label: nsubj root case obl punct amod nsubj cc amod conj aux ccomp compound compound obj case nummod obl punct

text: As coauthor Colette Heald told The Huffington Post , " The climate projections are quite consistent [...]
label: mark nsubj compound appos advcl det compound iobj punct punct det compound nsubj cop advmod root punct

text: the future of ozone pollution is very different [...] leading to either offsetting or reinforcing effects [ of climate change ] on crops " .
label: det nsubj case compound nmod cop advmod root punct advcl case cc amod cc conj obl punct case compound nmod punct case nmod punct punct

text: By 2050 , undernourishment would increase by either 49 percent or by 27 percent , depending on the scenario .
label: case obl punct nsubj aux root case cc nummod obl cc case nummod conj punct case fixed det obl punct

text: The study focuses on ozone - temperature covariation : ground - level ozone increases with temperatures .
label: det nsubj root case compound punct compound obl punct compound punct compound nsubj parataxis case obl punct

text: Heald said although temperature and ozone are separately known to impact crop yields , " nobody has looked at these together " .
label: nsubj root mark nsubj cc conj aux advmod advcl mark xcomp compound obj punct punct nsubj aux ccomp case obl advmod punct punct

text: Depending on region and crops , the yields may be primarily sensitive to ozone - in the case of wheat - or heat - in the case of maize - alone , providing a local estimation of relative benefits of climate change adaptation versus ozone regulation .
label: case fixed obl cc conj punct det nsubj aux cop advmod root case obl punct case det nmod case nmod punct cc conj punct case det nmod case nmod punct advmod punct advcl det amod obj case amod nmod case compound compound nmod case compound nmod punct

text: The U.S. Department of Agriculture notes , " Ground - level ozone causes more damage to plants than all other air pollutants combined " , highlighting the importance of air quality for agriculture .
label: det compound nsubj case nmod root punct punct compound punct compound nsubj dep amod obj case obl case det amod compound nmod acl punct punct xcomp det obj case compound nmod case nmod punct

text: Results of NCLAN studies , published in a paper by AS Heagle in 1989 , show dicot species , such as soybean , cotton , and peanut , lose more yield from ozone than do monocot species such as sorghum , field corn , and winter wheat .
label: nsubj case compound nmod punct acl case det obl case nmod flat case obl punct root compound nsubj punct case fixed nmod punct conj punct cc conj punct ccomp amod obj case obl mark acl compound nsubj case fixed nmod punct compound conj punct cc compound conj punct

text: The researchers found that ozone pollution caused 46 percent of previously heat - attributed damage to soybean crops .
label: det nsubj root mark compound nsubj ccomp nummod obj case advmod compound punct amod nmod case compound nmod punct

text: The model does not include the effect of rising carbon dioxide concentration , which has complex and potentially offsetting impacts on global food supply .
label: det nsubj aux advmod root det obj case amod compound compound nmod punct nsubj acl amod cc conj amod obj case amod compound nmod punct

text: The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency says some crops may have higher yields with increased levels of carbon dioxide .

text: August 08 , 1974

text: Good evening :

text: This is the 37th time I have spoken to you from this office , where so many decisions have been made that shaped the history of this Nation .
label: nsubj cop det amod root nsubj aux acl case obl case det obl punct advmod advmod amod nsubj aux aux acl nsubj acl det obj case det nmod punct

label: case det det obl nsubj aux acl case nmod amod obl punct nsubj aux advmod root mark xcomp obj cop acl case det obl punct

text: Throughout the long and difficult period of Watergate , I have felt it was my duty to persevere , to make every possible effort to complete the term of office to which you elected me .
label: case det amod cc conj obl case nmod punct nsubj aux root expl cop nmod ccomp mark csubj punct mark conj det amod obj mark acl det obj case nmod case obl nsubj acl obj punct

text: In the past few days , however , it has become evident to me that I no longer have a strong enough political base in the Congress to justify continuing that effort .
label: case det amod amod obl punct advmod punct expl aux root xcomp case obl mark nsubj advmod advmod csubj det amod advmod amod obj case det nmod mark advcl xcomp det obj punct

text: As long as there was such a base , I felt strongly that it was necessary to see the constitutional process through to its conclusion , that to do otherwise would be unfaithful to the spirit of that deliberately difficult process and a dangerously destabilizing precedent for the future .
label: advmod advmod mark expl advcl det det nsubj punct nsubj root advmod mark expl cop ccomp mark csubj det amod obj compound case nmod obl punct mark mark csubj advmod aux cop conj case det obl case det advmod amod nmod cc det advmod amod conj case det nmod punct

text: I would have preferred to carry through to the finish , whatever the personal agony it would have involved , and my family unanimously urged me to do so .

text: But the interests of the Nation must always come before any personal considerations .

text: From the discussions I have had with Congressional and other leaders , I have concluded that because of the Watergate matter , I might not have the support of the Congress that I would consider necessary to back the very difficult decisions and carry out the duties of this office in the way the interests of the Nation will require .
label: case det obl nsubj aux acl case amod cc conj obl punct nsubj aux root mark case fixed det compound obl punct nsubj aux advmod ccomp det obj case det nmod obj nsubj aux acl xcomp mark advcl det advmod amod obj cc conj compound det obj case det nmod case det obl det nsubj case det nmod aux acl punct

text: To continue to fight through the months ahead for my personal vindication would almost totally absorb the time and attention of both the President and the Congress in a period when our entire focus should be on the great issues of peace abroad and prosperity without inflation at home .
label: mark csubj mark xcomp case det obl advmod case nmod amod obl aux advmod advmod root det obj cc conj case cc det nmod cc det conj case det obl advmod nmod amod nsubj aux cop case det amod acl case nmod advmod cc conj case nmod case nmod punct

text: Therefore , I shall resign the Presidency effective at noon tomorrow .

label: compound nsubj flat aux aux root compound case obl case det obl case det obl punct

text: As I recall the high hopes for America with which we began this second term , I feel a great sadness that I will not be here in this office working on your behalf to achieve those hopes in the next 2 1/2 years .
label: mark nsubj advcl det amod obj case nmod case obl nsubj acl det amod obj punct nsubj root det amod obj mark nsubj aux advmod cop acl case det obl advcl case nmod obl mark advcl det obj case det amod nummod conj obl punct

text: But in turning over direction of the Government to Vice President Ford , I know , as I told the Nation when I nominated him for that office 10 months ago , that the leadership of America will be in good hands .
label: cc mark advcl compound obj case det nmod case compound obl flat punct nsubj root punct mark nsubj advcl det iobj advmod nsubj advcl obj case det obl nummod obl advmod punct mark det nsubj case nmod aux cop case amod ccomp punct

text: In passing this office to the Vice President , I also do so with the profound sense of the weight of responsibility that will fall on his shoulders tomorrow and , therefore , of the understanding , the patience , the cooperation he will need from all Americans .

label: mark nsubj advcl det obj punct nsubj aux root det obj cc det conj case nmod case nmod punct

text: As we look to the future , the first essential is to begin healing the wounds of this Nation , to put the bitterness and divisions of the recent past behind us and to rediscover those shared ideals that lie at the heart of our strength and unity as a great and as a free people .
label: mark nsubj advcl case det obl punct det amod nsubj cop mark root xcomp det obj case det nmod punct mark conj det obj cc conj case det amod nmod case xcomp cc mark conj det amod obj nsubj acl case det obl case nmod nmod cc conj case det amod cc case det conj nmod punct

text: By taking this action , I hope that I will have hastened the start of that process of healing which is so desperately needed in America .
label: mark advcl det obj punct nsubj root mark nsubj aux aux ccomp det obj case det nmod case nmod nsubj aux advmod advmod acl case obl punct

text: I regret deeply any injuries that may have been done in the course of the events that led to this decision .
label: nsubj root advmod det obj nsubj aux aux aux acl case det obl case det nmod nsubj acl case det obl punct

text: I would say only that if some of my judgments were wrong -- and some were wrong -- they were made in what I believed at the time to be the best interest of the Nation .

text: To those who have stood with me during these past difficult months -- to my family , my friends , to many others who joined in supporting my cause because they believed it was right -- I will be eternally grateful for your support .
label: case obl nsubj aux acl case obl case det amod amod obl punct case nmod parataxis punct nmod conj punct case amod conj nsubj acl mark advcl nmod obj mark nsubj advcl nsubj cop ccomp punct nsubj aux cop advmod root case nmod obl punct

label: cc case obl nsubj aux advmod acl xcomp mark xcomp iobj nmod obj punct root obj xcomp nsubj ccomp case det obl case nmod nsubj aux acl obj punct mark nsubj case nmod punct case det amod obl punct aux cop advcl case det obl case det nmod punct advmod nmod nsubj aux advcl punct

text: So , let us all now join together in affirming that common commitment and in helping our new President succeed for the benefit of all Americans .

label: nsubj cop root mark xcomp advmod case obl cc conj nmod amod obj punct

label: nsubj aux root obj det nsubj aux advmod advcl obj punct cc punct case det obl punct case obl nsubj acl case det amod obl punct case obl nsubj acl mark det amod nsubj aux ccomp obj case det nmod punct det conj punct cc det conj punct nsubj cop conj mark cop xcomp case obl punct

text: Concepts and Prototypes
label: root cc conj

text: The human nervous system is capable of handling endless streams of information .

text: To make this process more complex , the brain does not gather information from external environments only .

text: When thoughts are formed , the brain also pulls information from emotions and memories ( Figure 7.2 ) .

text: In order to organize this staggering amount of information , the brain has developed a file cabinet of sorts in the mind .

text: The different files stored in the file cabinet are called concepts .

text: Concepts are informed by our semantic memory ( you will learn more about semantic memory in a later chapter ) and are present in every aspect of our lives ; however , one of the easiest places to notice concepts is inside a classroom , where they are discussed explicitly .

label: case det obl punct nmod nsubj root obj nsubj acl cc conj nmod obj case amod nmod case nmod punct conj punct cc conj punct

text: Are there Moral Facts ?
label: root expl amod nsubj punct

text: So far , we have covered how evolutionary ethics relates to the question what we ought to do and why we are moral in the first place .
label: advmod advmod punct nsubj aux root obj amod nsubj advcl case det obl obj nsubj acl mark xcomp cc advmod nsubj cop conj case det amod obl punct

text: A related set of questions about ethics are metaethical questions , which concern the meaning of moral terms , our ways of gaining knowledge of moral facts , and the nature of the moral facts .
label: det amod nsubj case nmod case nmod cop amod root punct nsubj acl det obj case amod nmod punct nmod conj mark acl obj case amod nmod punct cc det conj case det amod nmod punct

text: In other words , apart from thinking about how we ought to live , and where our moral sense comes from , we can also ask what it means to affirm a particular answer to that question , how we could come to know the answer , and whether the answer would be a matter of fact or more like an opinion .
label: case amod obl punct advmod mark advcl case obl nsubj advcl mark xcomp punct cc conj nmod amod nsubj advcl obl punct nsubj aux advmod root obj expl acl mark csubj det amod obj case det nmod punct conj nsubj aux advcl mark xcomp det obj punct cc mark det nsubj aux cop det conj case nmod cc advmod case det conj punct

text: Many books and articles in moral philosophy start with the observation that moral judgments seem to be objectively true and the assumption that this is how non-philosophers also think about morality .
label: amod nsubj cc conj case amod nmod root case det obl mark amod nsubj acl mark cop advmod xcomp cc det conj mark nsubj cop acl nsubj advmod advcl case obl punct

text: For example , Michael Smith writes :
label: case obl punct nsubj flat root punct

text: We seem to think moral questions have correct answers ; that the correct answers are made correct by objective moral facts ; that moral facts are wholly determined by circumstances ; and that , by engaging in moral conversation and argument , we can discover what these objective facts are .
label: nsubj root mark xcomp amod nsubj ccomp amod obj punct mark det amod nsubj aux conj xcomp case amod amod obl punct mark amod nsubj aux advmod conj case obl punct cc mark punct mark advcl case amod obl cc conj punct nsubj aux conj obj det amod nsubj acl punct
punct root nmod punct dep punct

text: But as we have seen above , evolutionary theory explains why we would think that moral judgments are objective .
label: cc mark nsubj aux advcl advmod punct amod nsubj root obj nsubj aux advcl mark amod nsubj cop ccomp punct

text: The philosopher Michael Ruse takes this to show that the apparent objectivity of morality is something like an ‚Äú illusion ‚Äù foisted on us by our genes ( Ruse [ 1986 ] 1998 , 253 ) .
label: det nsubj appos flat root obj mark xcomp mark det amod nsubj case nmod cop ccomp case det punct nmod punct acl case obl case nmod obl punct dep punct nmod punct nmod punct dep punct punct

text: Of course , even if Ruse is correct , this does not show that moral judgments are not objective , but it can make us think whether the objectivity of morality really has to be explained , as many philosophers assume .
label: advmod fixed punct advmod mark nsubj cop advcl punct nsubj aux advmod root mark amod nsubj cop advmod ccomp punct cc nsubj aux conj obj xcomp mark det nsubj case nmod advmod ccomp mark aux xcomp punct mark amod nsubj advcl punct

text: Ruse has also argued that an evolutionary account of morality suggests that there are no moral facts in the first place .
label: nsubj aux advmod root mark det amod nsubj case nmod ccomp mark expl ccomp det amod nsubj case det amod obl punct

text: Anything we want to explain about morality can be explained without mentioning moral facts , or so Ruse argues .
label: nsubj nsubj acl mark xcomp case nmod aux aux root mark advcl amod obj punct cc advmod nsubj conj punct

text: If moral facts are explanatorily redundant , indeed , moral realists ( those who believe there are mind - independent , objective facts about morality , as discussed in Chapter 1 ) need to say why we should still suppose that moral facts do exist .
label: mark amod nsubj cop advmod advcl punct advmod punct amod nsubj punct appos nsubj acl expl ccomp compound punct amod punct amod nsubj case nmod punct mark acl case obl nummod punct root mark xcomp obj nsubj aux advmod advcl mark amod nsubj aux ccomp punct

text: Interestingly , Ruse ‚Äôs methodological naturalism leads him to embrace a view that goes against the metaphysical naturalist position that moral facts exist .
label: advmod punct nmod case amod nsubj root obj mark xcomp det obj nsubj acl case det amod compound obl mark amod nsubj acl punct

text: Relatedly , Sharon Street , for example , argues that evolutionary explanations of morality show that moral realism is probably false .
label: advmod punct nsubj flat punct case obl punct root mark amod nsubj case nmod ccomp mark amod nsubj cop advmod ccomp punct

text: The kind of moral realism that Street has in mind is the view that moral properties exist as objective features of the world ( to wit , whether stealing is wrong is independent of whether anyone thinks or feels that stealing is wrong ) .
label: det nsubj case amod nmod obj nsubj acl case obl cop det root mark amod nsubj acl case amod obl case det nmod punct mark advcl punct mark csubj cop csubj cop parataxis mark mark nsubj advcl cc conj mark csubj cop ccomp punct punct

text: Street starts with the premise that our moral judgments are influenced by evolutionary forces .
label: nsubj root case det obl mark nmod amod nsubj aux acl case amod obl punct

text: This fact , Street claims , gives rise to a dilemma for moral realists concerning the relation of the evolutionary forces that influenced our moral judgments and the moral facts claimed to exist by moral realists .

text: Can We have Justified Moral Beliefs ?
label: aux nsubj root amod amod obj punct

text: The evolutionary argument by Sharon Street can also be interpreted as an argument about moral justification and moral knowledge .

text: Suppose that moral realists assume that there is no relation between our moral judgments and the moral facts .

text: There are just too many possible moral truths and too many ways in which evolution could have ‚Äú pushed ‚Äù our moral beliefs .

text: Street claims that such a coincidence would be too much to believe .

text: But what is the problem , exactly , with having beliefs that are only coincidentally true ?

text: Depending on how we understand ‚Äú coincidence , ‚Äù my belief that there is a bird outside my window is coincidentally true because had I looked a little later , the bird would have flown away already .

text: Accidentally true beliefs do not seem problematic in every case .

text: The question for proponents of Street ‚Äôs argument is to show why the evolutionary influence on human moral beliefs makes for a particularly problematic case of coincidence .

text: The philosopher Richard Joyce argues that the problem has to do with the sensitivity of our moral beliefs to the moral facts ( Joyce 2006 ) .

text: But because we should not hold on to such insensitive beliefs , evolutionary explanations of morality show that our moral beliefs are unjustified ( because they are not sensitive ) .

text: The impact of evolutionary ethics on epistemological questions depends on these deeper questions about epistemology . [ 13 ]

text: Evolutionary explanations of morality , however , provide us with a useful starting point for thinking about these questions .

text: THE FIRST AMERICANS : THE OLMEC

text: Mesoamerica is the geographic area stretching from north of Panama up to the desert of central Mexico .

text: Ethnocentrism and Cultural Relativism
label: root cc amod conj

text: Despite how much humans have in common , cultural differences are far more prevalent than cultural universals .
label: case advmod obl nsubj acl case obl punct amod nsubj cop advmod advmod root case amod obl punct

text: For example , while all cultures have language , analysis of particular language structures and conversational etiquette reveal tremendous differences .
label: case obl punct mark det nsubj advcl obj punct nsubj case amod compound nmod cc amod conj root amod obj punct

text: In some Middle Eastern cultures , it is common to stand close to others in conversation .
label: case det amod amod obl punct expl cop root mark csubj advmod case obl case obl punct

text: North Americans keep more distance and maintain a large ‚Äú personal space . ‚Äù
label: compound nsubj root amod obj cc conj det amod punct amod obj punct punct

text: Even something as simple as eating and drinking varies greatly from culture to culture .
label: advmod nsubj advmod amod mark advcl cc conj root advmod case obl case obl punct

text: If your professor comes into an early morning class holding a mug of liquid , what do you assume she is drinking ?
label: mark nmod nsubj advcl case det amod compound obl advcl det obj case nmod punct obj aux nsubj root nsubj aux ccomp punct

text: In the United States , it ‚Äôs most likely filled with coffee , not Earl Grey tea , a favorite in England , or Yak Butter tea , a staple in Tibet .
label: case det amod obl punct nsubj aux advmod advmod root case obl punct advmod compound flat conj punct det appos case nmod punct cc compound compound conj punct det appos case nmod punct

text: The way cuisines vary across cultures fascinates many people .
label: det nsubj nsubj acl case obl root amod obj punct

text: Some travelers pride themselves on their willingness to try unfamiliar foods , like celebrated food writer Anthony Bourdain , while others return home expressing gratitude for their native culture ‚Äôs fare .
label: det nsubj root obj case nmod obl mark acl amod obj punct case amod compound compound obl flat punct mark nsubj advcl advmod advcl obj case nmod amod nmod case nmod punct

text: Often , people in the United States express disgust at other cultures ‚Äô cuisine and think that it ‚Äôs gross to eat meat from a dog or guinea pig , for example , while they do n‚Äôt question their own habit of eating cows or pigs .
label: advmod punct nsubj case det amod nmod root obj case amod nmod case nmod cc conj mark expl cop ccomp mark csubj obj case det nmod cc compound conj punct case obl punct mark nsubj aux advmod advcl nmod amod obj mark acl obj cc conj punct

text: Such attitudes are an example of ethnocentrism , or evaluating and judging another culture based on how it compares to one ‚Äôs own cultural norms .
label: amod nsubj cop det root case nmod punct cc conj cc conj det obj advcl mark obl nsubj advcl case nmod case amod amod obl punct

text: Ethnocentrism , as sociologist William Graham Sumner ( 1906 ) described the term , involves a belief or attitude that one ‚Äôs own culture is better than all others .
label: nsubj punct mark compound nsubj flat flat punct nmod punct advcl det obj punct root det obj cc conj mark nmod case amod nsubj cop acl case det obl punct

text: Almost everyone is a little bit ethnocentric .
label: advmod nsubj cop det amod obl root punct

text: For example , Americans tend to say that people from England drive on the ‚Äú wrong ‚Äù side of the road , rather than on the ‚Äú other ‚Äù side .
label: case obl punct nsubj root mark xcomp mark nsubj case nmod ccomp case det punct amod punct obl case det nmod punct cc fixed case det punct amod punct conj punct

text: Someone from a country where dog meat is standard fare might find it off - putting to see a dog in a French restaurant ‚Äî not on the menu , but as a pet and patron ‚Äôs companion .
label: nsubj case det nmod advmod compound nsubj cop amod acl aux root expl advmod punct xcomp mark xcomp det obj case det amod obl punct advmod case det obl punct cc case det conj cc nmod case conj punct

text: A good example of ethnocentrism is referring to parts of Asia as the " Far East . "
label: det amod nsubj case nmod cop root case obl case nmod case det punct amod obl punct punct

text: One might question , " Far east of where ? "
label: nsubj aux root punct punct advmod ccomp case obl punct punct

text: A high level of appreciation for one ‚Äôs own culture can be healthy ; a shared sense of community pride , for example , connects people in a society .
label: det amod nsubj case nmod case nmod case amod nmod aux cop root punct det amod nsubj case compound nmod punct case obl punct parataxis obj case det obl punct

text: But ethnocentrism can lead to disdain or dislike for other cultures and could cause misunderstanding and conflict .
label: cc nsubj aux root case obl cc conj case amod nmod cc aux conj obj cc conj punct

text: People with the best intentions sometimes travel to a society to ‚Äú help ‚Äù its people , because they see them as uneducated or backward - essentially inferior .
label: nsubj case det amod nmod advmod root case det obl mark punct advcl punct nmod obj punct mark nsubj advcl obj case obl cc conj punct advmod appos punct

text: In reality , these travelers are guilty of cultural imperialism , the deliberate imposition of one ‚Äôs own cultural values on another culture .
label: case obl punct det nsubj cop root case amod obl punct det amod appos case nmod case amod amod nmod case det nmod punct

text: Europe ‚Äôs colonial expansion , begun in the sixteenth century , was often accompanied by a severe cultural imperialism .
label: nmod case amod nsubj punct acl case det amod obl punct aux advmod root case det amod amod obl punct

text: European colonizers often viewed the people in the lands they colonized as uncultured savages who were in need of European governance , dress , religion , and other cultural practices .
label: amod nsubj advmod root det obj case det nmod nsubj acl case amod obl nsubj cop case acl case amod nmod punct conj punct conj punct cc amod amod conj punct

text: A more modern example of cultural imperialism may include the work of international aid agencies who introduce agricultural methods and plant species from developed countries while overlooking indigenous varieties and agricultural approaches that are better suited to the particular region .
label: det advmod amod nsubj case amod nmod aux root det obj case amod compound nmod nsubj acl amod obj cc compound conj case amod nmod mark advcl amod obj cc amod conj nsubj cop advmod acl case det amod obl punct

text: Ethnocentrism can be so strong that when confronted with all of the differences of a new culture , one may experience disorientation and frustration .
label: nsubj aux cop advmod root mark advmod advcl case obl case det nmod case det amod nmod punct nsubj aux advcl obj cc conj punct

text: In sociology , we call this culture shock .
label: case obl punct nsubj root obj compound xcomp punct

text: A traveler from Chicago might find the nightly silence of rural Montana unsettling , not peaceful .
label: det nsubj case nmod aux root det amod obj case amod nmod xcomp punct advmod conj punct

text: An exchange student from China might be annoyed by the constant interruptions in class as other students ask questions ‚Äî a practice that is considered rude in China .
label: det compound nsubj case nmod aux aux root case det amod obl case nmod mark amod nsubj acl obj punct det appos nsubj aux acl xcomp case obl punct

text: Perhaps the Chicago traveler was initially captivated with Montana ‚Äôs quiet beauty and the Chinese student was originally excited to see a U.S. - style classroom firsthand .
label: advmod det compound nsubj cop advmod root case nmod case amod obl cc det amod nsubj aux advmod conj mark xcomp det compound punct compound obj advmod punct

text: But as they experience unanticipated differences from their own culture , their excitement gives way to discomfort and doubts about how to behave appropriately in the new situation .
label: cc mark nsubj advcl amod obj case nmod amod nmod punct nmod nsubj root obl case obl cc conj case nmod mark acl advmod case det amod obl punct

text: Eventually , as people learn more about a culture , they recover from culture shock .
label: advmod punct mark nsubj advcl obj case det obl punct nsubj root case compound obl punct

text: Culture shock may appear because people are n‚Äôt always expecting cultural differences .
label: compound nsubj aux root mark nsubj aux advmod advmod advcl amod obj punct

text: Anthropologist Ken Barger ( 1971 ) discovered this when he conducted a participatory observation in an Inuit community in the Canadian Arctic .
label: nsubj flat flat punct nmod punct root obj advmod nsubj advcl det amod obj case det amod obl case det amod nmod punct

text: Originally from Indiana , Barger hesitated when invited to join a local snowshoe race .
label: advmod case obl punct nsubj root advmod advcl mark xcomp det amod compound obj punct

text: He knew he ‚Äôd never hold his own against these experts .
label: nsubj root nsubj aux advmod ccomp nmod obj case det obl punct

text: Sure enough , he finished last , to his mortification .
label: advmod advmod punct nsubj root advmod punct case nmod obl punct

text: But the tribal members congratulated him , saying , ‚Äú You really tried ! ‚Äù
label: cc det amod nsubj root obj punct advcl punct punct nsubj advmod ccomp punct punct

text: In Barger ‚Äôs own culture , he had learned to value victory .
label: case nmod case amod obl punct nsubj aux root mark xcomp obj punct

text: To the Inuit people , winning was enjoyable , but their culture valued survival skills essential to their environment : how hard someone tried could mean the difference between life and death .
label: case det amod obl punct csubj cop root punct cc nmod nsubj conj compound obj amod case nmod obl punct advmod csubj nsubj advcl aux parataxis det obj case nmod cc conj punct

text: Over the course of his stay , Barger participated in caribou hunts , learned how to take shelter in winter storms , and sometimes went days with little or no food to share among tribal members .
label: case det obl case nmod nmod punct nsubj root case compound obl punct conj obj mark acl obj case compound obl punct cc advmod conj obl case amod cc conj obl mark acl case amod obl punct

text: Trying hard and working together , two nonmaterial values , were indeed much more important than winning .
label: csubj advmod cc conj advmod punct nummod amod appos punct cop advmod advmod advmod root mark advcl punct

text: During his time with the Inuit tribe , Barger learned to engage in cultural relativism .
label: case nmod obl case det amod nmod punct nsubj root mark xcomp case amod obl punct

text: Cultural relativism is the practice of assessing a culture by its own standards rather than viewing it through the lens of one ‚Äôs own culture .
label: amod nsubj cop det root mark acl det obj case nmod amod obl cc fixed conj obj case det obl case nmod case amod nmod punct

text: Practicing cultural relativism requires an open mind and a willingness to consider , and even adapt to , new values and norms .
label: csubj amod obj root det amod obj cc det conj mark acl punct cc advmod conj obl punct amod obj cc conj punct

text: However , indiscriminately embracing everything about a new culture is not always possible .
label: advmod punct advmod csubj obj case det amod nmod cop advmod advmod root punct

text: Even the most culturally relativist people from egalitarian societies ‚Äî ones in which women have political rights and control over their own bodies ‚Äî would question whether the widespread practice of female genital mutilation in countries such as Ethiopia and Sudan should be accepted as a part of cultural tradition .
label: advmod det advmod advmod amod nsubj case amod nmod punct appos case obl nsubj acl amod obj cc conj case nmod amod nmod punct aux root mark det amod nsubj case amod compound nmod case nmod case fixed nmod cc conj aux aux ccomp case det obl case amod nmod punct

text: Sociologists attempting to engage in cultural relativism , then , may struggle to reconcile aspects of their own culture with aspects of a culture that they are studying .
label: nsubj acl mark xcomp case amod obl punct advmod punct aux root mark xcomp obj case nmod amod nmod case obl case det nmod obj nsubj aux acl punct

text: Sometimes when people attempt to rectify feelings of ethnocentrism and develop cultural relativism , they swing too far to the other end of the spectrum .
label: advmod advmod nsubj advcl mark xcomp obj case nmod cc conj amod obj punct nsubj root advmod advmod case det amod obl case det nmod punct

text: Xenocentrism is the opposite of ethnocentrism , and refers to the belief that another culture is superior to one ‚Äôs own .
label: nsubj cop det root case nmod punct cc conj case det obl mark det nsubj cop acl case nmod case obl punct

text: ( The Greek root word xeno , pronounced ‚Äú ZEE-no , ‚Äù means ‚Äú stranger ‚Äù or ‚Äú foreign guest . ‚Äù )
label: punct det amod compound nsubj appos punct acl punct xcomp punct punct root punct obj punct cc punct amod conj punct punct punct

text: An exchange student who goes home after a semester abroad or a sociologist who returns from the field may find it difficult to associate with the values of their own culture after having experienced what they deem a more upright or nobler way of living .

text: LEARNING OBJECTIVES

text: By the end of this section , you will be able to :

text: Understand that Newton ‚Äôs concept of the gravitational force between two massive objects and Einstein ‚Äôs concept of warped spacetime are different explanations for the same observed accelerations of one massive object in the presence of another massive object
label: root mark nmod case nsubj case det amod nmod case nummod amod nmod cc nmod case conj case amod nmod cop amod ccomp case det amod amod nmod case nummod amod nmod case det nmod case det amod nmod

text: Is light actually bent from its straight - line path by the mass of Earth ?

text: Einstein preferred to think that it is space and time that are affected by the presence of a large mass ; light beams , and everything else that travels through space and time , then find their paths affected .

text: Linkages : Mass , Space , and Time

text: To show what Einstein ‚Äôs insight really means , let ‚Äôs first consider how we locate an event in space and time .
label: mark advcl obj nmod case nsubj advmod acl punct root obj advmod xcomp obj nsubj advcl det obj case obl cc conj punct

text: For example , imagine you have to describe to worried school officials the fire that broke out in your room when your roommate tried cooking shish kebabs in the fireplace .

text: You explain that your dorm is at 6400 College Avenue , a street that runs in the left - right direction on a map of your town ; you are on the fifth floor , which tells where you are in the up - down direction ; and you are the sixth room back from the elevator , which tells where you are in the forward - backward direction .
label: nsubj root mark nmod nsubj cop case nummod compound ccomp punct det appos nsubj acl case det compound punct conj obl case det obl case nmod nmod punct nsubj cop case det amod conj punct nsubj acl obj nsubj advcl case det compound punct conj obl punct cc nsubj cop det amod conj advmod case det obl punct nsubj acl obj nsubj advcl case det compound punct conj obl punct

text: Any event in the universe , whether nearby or far away , can be pinpointed using the three dimensions of space and the one dimension of time .

text: But Einstein showed that there is an intimate connection between space and time , and that only by considering the two together ‚Äî in what we call spacetime ‚Äî can we build up a correct picture of the physical world .

text: We examine spacetime a bit more closely in the next subsection .

text: The gist of Einstein ‚Äôs general theory is that the presence of matter curves or warps the fabric of spacetime .

text: This curving of spacetime is identified with gravity .

text: When something else ‚Äî a beam of light , an electron , or the starship Enterprise ‚Äî enters such a region of distorted spacetime , its path will be different from what it would have been in the absence of the matter .
label: advmod nsubj advmod punct det appos case nmod punct det conj punct cc det conj appos punct advcl det det obj case amod nmod punct nmod nsubj aux cop root case obl nsubj aux aux acl case det obl case det nmod punct

text: As American physicist John Wheeler summarized it : ‚Äú Matter tells spacetime how to curve ; spacetime tells matter how to move . ‚Äù
label: mark amod nsubj flat flat advcl obj punct punct nsubj root iobj obj mark acl punct nsubj parataxis iobj obj mark acl punct punct

text: The amount of distortion in spacetime depends on the mass of material that is involved and on how concentrated and compact it is .

text: General relativity does , however , have some practical applications .

text: The GPS ( Global Positioning System ) in every smartphone can tell you where you are within 5 to 10 meters only because the effects of general and special relativity on the GPS satellites in orbit around the Earth are taken into account .

text: Unlike a book or your roommate , stars produce measurable distortions in spacetime .

text: 2.3 Measures of the Location of the Data

text: The common measures of location are quartiles and percentiles .
label: det amod nsubj case nmod cop root cc conj punct

text: Quartiles are special percentiles .

text: The first quartile , Q 1 , is the same as the 25th percentile , and the third quartile , Q 3 , is the same as the 75th percentile .

text: The median , M , is called both the second quartile and the 50th percentile .
